How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist block, since travel in the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on vacations at the RDA (Germany Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) in Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslavia regime moved west and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great barrier to socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist block (i.e., also the Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely and individually, not even by the Socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to put on the cola with a bed bag and spend the whole night, or having "good-known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for Western travel was not granted to the "politically low-liquid agent", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs had their vacations in their own country, so there were a large number of horses and summer houses that the Czechs would buy. This custom still persisted.
The way the Czechs travel has suffered a genuine revolution since 1989.
While it was not until 1989 for us that the holidays were no longer in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, from which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, was unable to travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia from then on.
At the beginning of the 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighboring countries of Western Europe, resulting in a huge amount of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechs, for a long time, did not see maps of the trips to the West, the whole world wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, checkups were slept in parks in camp stores, as our income did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to bring with them food (conservations, embutites, etc.) to store.
Another important moment was the introduction of the conversion of the Czech crown, so our tourists were finally able, after decades, to buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living also increased the average wage, which has resulted in an increase in the demand for travel by around 1997.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies from 1997 onwards regularly began to prepare travel using charter flights, which made the prices of travel in comparison with the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by passenger volume.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs had traveled almost all developed countries, except the United States, which made our journeys even more simple.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-conflict tourism occurred already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Chequia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have made distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Chequia to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-conflict development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, with what our country had gone through to be among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent abroad on trips to over 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses at the station.
