Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for employment.
The XV Week for the use of disabled people starts today.
Despite a public policy that has been implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disappointment?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the use of disabled persons.
"The progress achieved five years ago is considerable.
"At that time the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still a lot to do."
It should be noted that disabled persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They usually have a higher age: 37% is over 50 years of age (about 17% of the average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% has not completed the education and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, the long-term wall is very extensive among them: 53 per cent for disabled persons, compared to 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are many issues that are particularly difficult to return to the working world and that "constitutually constitute the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mental attitude progresses, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneurship for the City indicated that the respondents had "a level of knowledge on low disability", with "excessive representation of people in the street, physical or intellectual deficits".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hireing 6% of disabled workers, the objective of which was laid down in a Act of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures from 2008, a ratio of 2.6 per cent is reached.
"We now reach around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for withdrawing the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The evidence: the number of establishment "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts paid, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated a great pressure on businesses," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also reflects true consciousness, especially among the great groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies with between 20 and 49 employees have employees who are disabled in their schedule, compared to 82 per cent of the companies between 100 and 199 workers.
